Note:
PowerPC Instruction Encoder - Binary Machine Code Encoding

This file encodes PowerPC instructions into their fixed 32-bit binary
representations according to the PowerPC ISA. All PowerPC instructions are
exactly 32 bits wide, encoded in several distinct formats:

  D-form:  |opcode(6)|RT(5)|RA(5)|D(16)|
  X-form:  |opcode(6)|RT(5)|RA(5)|RB(5)|XO(10)|Rc(1)|
  XO-form: |opcode(6)|RT(5)|RA(5)|RB(5)|OE(1)|XO(9)|Rc(1)|
  B-form:  |opcode(6)|BO(5)|BI(5)|BD(14)|AA(1)|LK(1)|
  I-form:  |opcode(6)|LI(24)|AA(1)|LK(1)|
  M-form:  |opcode(6)|RS(5)|RA(5)|RB(5)|MB(5)|ME(5)|Rc(1)|
  XL-form: |opcode(6)|BT(5)|BA(5)|BB(5)|XO(10)|LK(1)|

This file performs the following tasks:
- Encode D-form instructions (loads, stores, immediate ALU operations)
- Encode X-form instructions (register ALU operations, compares)
- Encode XO-form instructions (arithmetic with overflow detection)
- Encode B-form instructions (conditional branches)
- Encode I-form instructions (unconditional branches)
- Encode special instructions (SC syscall, mflr, mtlr, mfctr, mtctr, blr)

This file is essential because of the following reasons:
- Correct binary encoding produces valid PowerPC machine code
- PowerPC has multiple instruction formats requiring format-aware encoding
- Branch and link semantics (LK bit) must be correctly encoded
- Condition register field encoding is critical for correct branching

This file consists of the following functions/features/operation types:
- Per-format encoding functions (D, X, XO, B, I forms)
- Common instruction encoders (add, lwz, stw, bc, b, bl, sc)
- Branch condition encoding with BO/BI field computation
- Bit manipulation utilities for field placement

Dependencies:
- Imports Layout for output buffer allocation
- Imports List for instruction buffer management
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/lir.runa" as LIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/lir_nodes.runa" as LIRNodes
Import "compiler/backend/machine_code/common/machine_code_interface.runa" as MachineCode
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List

Note: ============================================================================
Note: POWERPC OPCODE CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
PowerPC uses a 6-bit primary opcode field (bits 31:26) to identify the
instruction format and general operation class. Within each format, extended
opcode (XO) fields further specify the exact operation.

Primary opcodes for common instruction groups:
- D-form loads/stores use opcodes 32-55
- D-form immediate ALU uses opcodes 8-15
- X-form/XO-form ALU uses primary opcode 31 with extended opcodes
- B-form conditional branches use opcode 16
- I-form unconditional branches use opcode 18
- SC syscall uses opcode 17
@End Reasoning

Note: Primary opcodes
Constant PPC_OP_TWI as Integer is 3
Constant PPC_OP_MULLI as Integer is 7
Constant PPC_OP_SUBFIC as Integer is 8
Constant PPC_OP_CMPLI as Integer is 10
Constant PPC_OP_CMPI as Integer is 11
Constant PPC_OP_ADDIC as Integer is 12
Constant PPC_OP_ADDIC_DOT as Integer is 13
Constant PPC_OP_ADDI as Integer is 14
Constant PPC_OP_ADDIS as Integer is 15
Constant PPC_OP_BC as Integer is 16     Note: Conditional branch (B-form)
Constant PPC_OP_SC as Integer is 17     Note: System call
Constant PPC_OP_B as Integer is 18      Note: Unconditional branch (I-form)
Constant PPC_OP_BCLR as Integer is 19   Note: Branch conditional to LR/CTR (XL-form)
Constant PPC_OP_RLWIMI as Integer is 20
Constant PPC_OP_RLWINM as Integer is 21
Constant PPC_OP_RLWNM as Integer is 23
Constant PPC_OP_ORI as Integer is 24
Constant PPC_OP_ORIS as Integer is 25
Constant PPC_OP_XORI as Integer is 26
Constant PPC_OP_XORIS as Integer is 27
Constant PPC_OP_ANDI_DOT as Integer is 28
Constant PPC_OP_ANDIS_DOT as Integer is 29
Constant PPC_OP_ALU_EXT as Integer is 31  Note: Extended ALU (X/XO-form)
Constant PPC_OP_LWZ as Integer is 32
Constant PPC_OP_LWZU as Integer is 33
Constant PPC_OP_LBZ as Integer is 34
Constant PPC_OP_LBZU as Integer is 35
Constant PPC_OP_STW as Integer is 36
Constant PPC_OP_STWU as Integer is 37
Constant PPC_OP_STB as Integer is 38
Constant PPC_OP_STBU as Integer is 39
Constant PPC_OP_LHZ as Integer is 40
Constant PPC_OP_LHZU as Integer is 41
Constant PPC_OP_LHA as Integer is 42
Constant PPC_OP_LHAU as Integer is 43
Constant PPC_OP_STH as Integer is 44
Constant PPC_OP_STHU as Integer is 45
Constant PPC_OP_LFS as Integer is 48
Constant PPC_OP_LFSU as Integer is 49
Constant PPC_OP_LFD as Integer is 50
Constant PPC_OP_LFDU as Integer is 51
Constant PPC_OP_STFS as Integer is 52
Constant PPC_OP_STFSU as Integer is 53
Constant PPC_OP_STFD as Integer is 54
Constant PPC_OP_STFDU as Integer is 55

Note: Extended opcodes for opcode 31 (X/XO-form)
Constant PPC_XO_CMP as Integer is 0
Constant PPC_XO_SUBFC as Integer is 8
Constant PPC_XO_ADDC as Integer is 10
Constant PPC_XO_MULHWU as Integer is 11
Constant PPC_XO_MFCR as Integer is 19
Constant PPC_XO_LWZX as Integer is 23
Constant PPC_XO_SLW as Integer is 24
Constant PPC_XO_CNTLZW as Integer is 26
Constant PPC_XO_AND as Integer is 28
Constant PPC_XO_CMPL as Integer is 32
Constant PPC_XO_SUBF as Integer is 40
Constant PPC_XO_ANDC as Integer is 60
Constant PPC_XO_MULHW as Integer is 75
Constant PPC_XO_MFMSR as Integer is 83
Constant PPC_XO_STWX as Integer is 151
Constant PPC_XO_MTCRF as Integer is 144
Constant PPC_XO_NEG as Integer is 104
Constant PPC_XO_NOR as Integer is 124
Constant PPC_XO_SUBFE as Integer is 136
Constant PPC_XO_ADDE as Integer is 138
Constant PPC_XO_MULLW as Integer is 235
Constant PPC_XO_ADD as Integer is 266
Constant PPC_XO_LHZX as Integer is 279
Constant PPC_XO_XOR as Integer is 316
Constant PPC_XO_MFSPR as Integer is 339
Constant PPC_XO_LHAX as Integer is 343
Constant PPC_XO_STHX as Integer is 407
Constant PPC_XO_OR as Integer is 444
Constant PPC_XO_DIVWU as Integer is 459
Constant PPC_XO_MTSPR as Integer is 467
Constant PPC_XO_DIVW as Integer is 491
Constant PPC_XO_SRW as Integer is 536
Constant PPC_XO_SRAW as Integer is 792
Constant PPC_XO_SRAWI as Integer is 824
Constant PPC_XO_EXTSB as Integer is 954
Constant PPC_XO_EXTSH as Integer is 922

Note: Extended opcodes for opcode 19 (XL-form, branch to LR/CTR)
Constant PPC_XO_BCLR as Integer is 16   Note: Branch conditional to Link Register
Constant PPC_XO_BCCTR as Integer is 528 Note: Branch conditional to Count Register

Note: SPR numbers for MFSPR/MTSPR
Constant PPC_SPR_LR as Integer is 256   Note: Link Register (encoded as 8 in split form)
Constant PPC_SPR_CTR as Integer is 288  Note: Count Register (encoded as 9 in split form)

Note: Branch condition BO field encodings
Constant PPC_BO_ALWAYS as Integer is 20        Note: 10100: branch always
Constant PPC_BO_TRUE as Integer is 12          Note: 01100: branch if CR bit is true
Constant PPC_BO_FALSE as Integer is 4          Note: 00100: branch if CR bit is false
Constant PPC_BO_DNZ as Integer is 16           Note: 10000: decrement CTR, branch if nonzero
Constant PPC_BO_DZ as Integer is 18            Note: 10010: decrement CTR, branch if zero

Note: CR bit indices for BI field (within CR0)
Constant PPC_BI_LT as Integer is 0   Note: Less than
Constant PPC_BI_GT as Integer is 1   Note: Greater than
Constant PPC_BI_EQ as Integer is 2   Note: Equal
Constant PPC_BI_SO as Integer is 3   Note: Summary overflow

Note: ============================================================================
Note: BIT MANIPULATION HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "mask_bits" that takes value as Integer, bits as Integer returns Integer:
    Let mask be 1
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than bits:
        Set mask to mask multiplied by 2
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Set mask to mask minus 1
    If value is less than 0:
        Let adjusted be value plus mask plus 1
        Return adjusted minus ((adjusted divided by (mask plus 1)) multiplied by (mask plus 1))
    End If
    Return value minus ((value divided by (mask plus 1)) multiplied by (mask plus 1))
End Process

Process called "shift_left" that takes value as Integer, amount as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be value
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than amount:
        Set result to result multiplied by 2
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: FORMAT ENCODERS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "encode_d_form" that takes opcode as Integer, rt as Integer, ra as Integer, d as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Encodes a D-form instruction: |opcode(6)|RT(5)|RA(5)|D(16)|
    Used for loads, stores, and immediate ALU operations.
    D is a 16-bit signed displacement or immediate value.
    @End Reasoning

    Let encoded be shift_left(mask_bits(opcode, 6), 26)
    Set encoded to encoded plus shift_left(mask_bits(rt, 5), 21)
    Set encoded to encoded plus shift_left(mask_bits(ra, 5), 16)
    Set encoded to encoded plus mask_bits(d, 16)
    Return encoded
End Process

Process called "encode_x_form" that takes opcode as Integer, rt as Integer, ra as Integer, rb as Integer, xo as Integer, rc as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Encodes an X-form instruction: |opcode(6)|RT(5)|RA(5)|RB(5)|XO(10)|Rc(1)|
    Used for register-register ALU operations and comparisons.
    Rc=1 sets condition register based on the result (. suffix in assembly).
    @End Reasoning

    Let encoded be shift_left(mask_bits(opcode, 6), 26)
    Set encoded to encoded plus shift_left(mask_bits(rt, 5), 21)
    Set encoded to encoded plus shift_left(mask_bits(ra, 5), 16)
    Set encoded to encoded plus shift_left(mask_bits(rb, 5), 11)
    Set encoded to encoded plus shift_left(mask_bits(xo, 10), 1)
    Set encoded to encoded plus mask_bits(rc, 1)
    Return encoded
End Process

Process called "encode_xo_form" that takes opcode as Integer, rt as Integer, ra as Integer, rb as Integer, oe as Integer, xo as Integer, rc as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Encodes an XO-form instruction: |opcode(6)|RT(5)|RA(5)|RB(5)|OE(1)|XO(9)|Rc(1)|
    Used for arithmetic operations with optional overflow detection.
    OE=1 enables setting the OV (overflow) and SO (summary overflow) bits in XER.
    @End Reasoning

    Let encoded be shift_left(mask_bits(opcode, 6), 26)
    Set encoded to encoded plus shift_left(mask_bits(rt, 5), 21)
    Set encoded to encoded plus shift_left(mask_bits(ra, 5), 16)
    Set encoded to encoded plus shift_left(mask_bits(rb, 5), 11)
    Set encoded to encoded plus shift_left(mask_bits(oe, 1), 10)
    Set encoded to encoded plus shift_left(mask_bits(xo, 9), 1)
    Set encoded to encoded plus mask_bits(rc, 1)
    Return encoded
End Process

Process called "encode_b_form" that takes opcode as Integer, bo as Integer, bi as Integer, bd as Integer, aa as Integer, lk as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Encodes a B-form instruction: |opcode(6)|BO(5)|BI(5)|BD(14)|AA(1)|LK(1)|
    Used for conditional branches.
    BO specifies the branch condition type.
    BI specifies which CR bit to test.
    BD is a 14-bit signed branch displacement (word-aligned).
    AA=1 means absolute address; AA=0 means PC-relative.
    LK=1 means save return address in LR (branch and link).
    @End Reasoning

    Let encoded be shift_left(mask_bits(opcode, 6), 26)
    Set encoded to encoded plus shift_left(mask_bits(bo, 5), 21)
    Set encoded to encoded plus shift_left(mask_bits(bi, 5), 16)
    Set encoded to encoded plus shift_left(mask_bits(bd, 14), 2)
    Set encoded to encoded plus shift_left(mask_bits(aa, 1), 1)
    Set encoded to encoded plus mask_bits(lk, 1)
    Return encoded
End Process

Process called "encode_i_form" that takes opcode as Integer, li as Integer, aa as Integer, lk as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Encodes an I-form instruction: |opcode(6)|LI(24)|AA(1)|LK(1)|
    Used for unconditional branches (B, BL, BA, BLA).
    LI is a 24-bit signed offset (word-aligned, so effective range is 26 bits).
    LK=1 saves return address in LR (function call semantics).
    @End Reasoning

    Let encoded be shift_left(mask_bits(opcode, 6), 26)
    Set encoded to encoded plus shift_left(mask_bits(li, 24), 2)
    Set encoded to encoded plus shift_left(mask_bits(aa, 1), 1)
    Set encoded to encoded plus mask_bits(lk, 1)
    Return encoded
End Process

Process called "encode_xl_form" that takes opcode as Integer, bt as Integer, ba as Integer, bb as Integer, xo as Integer, lk as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Encodes an XL-form instruction: |opcode(6)|BT(5)|BA(5)|BB(5)|XO(10)|LK(1)|
    Used for branch to LR (bclr, blr) and branch to CTR (bcctr, bctr).
    @End Reasoning

    Let encoded be shift_left(mask_bits(opcode, 6), 26)
    Set encoded to encoded plus shift_left(mask_bits(bt, 5), 21)
    Set encoded to encoded plus shift_left(mask_bits(ba, 5), 16)
    Set encoded to encoded plus shift_left(mask_bits(bb, 5), 11)
    Set encoded to encoded plus shift_left(mask_bits(xo, 10), 1)
    Set encoded to encoded plus mask_bits(lk, 1)
    Return encoded
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ARITHMETIC INSTRUCTION ENCODERS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "encode_add" that takes rt as Integer, ra as Integer, rb as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: ADD rt, ra, rb: rt = ra + rb (XO-form, opcode 31, XO 266)
    Return encode_xo_form(PPC_OP_ALU_EXT, rt, ra, rb, 0, PPC_XO_ADD, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_addi" that takes rt as Integer, ra as Integer, si as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: ADDI rt, ra, SI: rt = ra + sign_extend(SI) (D-form, opcode 14)
    Return encode_d_form(PPC_OP_ADDI, rt, ra, si)
End Process

Process called "encode_addis" that takes rt as Integer, ra as Integer, si as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: ADDIS rt, ra, SI: rt = ra + (SI shifted left by 16) (D-form, opcode 15)
    Return encode_d_form(PPC_OP_ADDIS, rt, ra, si)
End Process

Process called "encode_subf" that takes rt as Integer, ra as Integer, rb as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: SUBF rt, ra, rb: rt = rb - ra (note operand order!) (XO-form, XO 40)
    Return encode_xo_form(PPC_OP_ALU_EXT, rt, ra, rb, 0, PPC_XO_SUBF, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_mullw" that takes rt as Integer, ra as Integer, rb as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: MULLW rt, ra, rb: rt = low32(ra * rb) (XO-form, XO 235)
    Return encode_xo_form(PPC_OP_ALU_EXT, rt, ra, rb, 0, PPC_XO_MULLW, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_divw" that takes rt as Integer, ra as Integer, rb as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: DIVW rt, ra, rb: rt = ra / rb (signed) (XO-form, XO 491)
    Return encode_xo_form(PPC_OP_ALU_EXT, rt, ra, rb, 0, PPC_XO_DIVW, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_divwu" that takes rt as Integer, ra as Integer, rb as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: DIVWU rt, ra, rb: rt = ra / rb (unsigned) (XO-form, XO 459)
    Return encode_xo_form(PPC_OP_ALU_EXT, rt, ra, rb, 0, PPC_XO_DIVWU, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_neg" that takes rt as Integer, ra as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: NEG rt, ra: rt = -ra (XO-form, XO 104)
    Return encode_xo_form(PPC_OP_ALU_EXT, rt, ra, 0, 0, PPC_XO_NEG, 0)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LOGICAL INSTRUCTION ENCODERS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "encode_and" that takes ra as Integer, rs as Integer, rb as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: AND ra, rs, rb: ra = rs AND rb (X-form, XO 28)
    Return encode_x_form(PPC_OP_ALU_EXT, rs, ra, rb, PPC_XO_AND, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_or" that takes ra as Integer, rs as Integer, rb as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: OR ra, rs, rb: ra = rs OR rb (X-form, XO 444)
    Return encode_x_form(PPC_OP_ALU_EXT, rs, ra, rb, PPC_XO_OR, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_xor" that takes ra as Integer, rs as Integer, rb as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: XOR ra, rs, rb: ra = rs XOR rb (X-form, XO 316)
    Return encode_x_form(PPC_OP_ALU_EXT, rs, ra, rb, PPC_XO_XOR, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_nor" that takes ra as Integer, rs as Integer, rb as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: NOR ra, rs, rb: ra = NOT(rs OR rb) (X-form, XO 124)
    Return encode_x_form(PPC_OP_ALU_EXT, rs, ra, rb, PPC_XO_NOR, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_ori" that takes ra as Integer, rs as Integer, ui as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: ORI ra, rs, UI: ra = rs OR zero_extend(UI) (D-form, opcode 24)
    Return encode_d_form(PPC_OP_ORI, rs, ra, ui)
End Process

Process called "encode_xori" that takes ra as Integer, rs as Integer, ui as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: XORI ra, rs, UI: ra = rs XOR zero_extend(UI) (D-form, opcode 26)
    Return encode_d_form(PPC_OP_XORI, rs, ra, ui)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SHIFT INSTRUCTION ENCODERS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "encode_slw" that takes ra as Integer, rs as Integer, rb as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: SLW ra, rs, rb: ra = rs shifted left by rb[4:0] (X-form, XO 24)
    Return encode_x_form(PPC_OP_ALU_EXT, rs, ra, rb, PPC_XO_SLW, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_srw" that takes ra as Integer, rs as Integer, rb as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: SRW ra, rs, rb: ra = rs shifted right by rb[4:0] (logical) (X-form, XO 536)
    Return encode_x_form(PPC_OP_ALU_EXT, rs, ra, rb, PPC_XO_SRW, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_sraw" that takes ra as Integer, rs as Integer, rb as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: SRAW ra, rs, rb: ra = rs shifted right by rb[4:0] (arithmetic) (X-form, XO 792)
    Return encode_x_form(PPC_OP_ALU_EXT, rs, ra, rb, PPC_XO_SRAW, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_srawi" that takes ra as Integer, rs as Integer, sh as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: SRAWI ra, rs, SH: ra = rs shifted right by SH (arithmetic, immediate) (X-form, XO 824)
    Return encode_x_form(PPC_OP_ALU_EXT, rs, ra, sh, PPC_XO_SRAWI, 0)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LOAD/STORE INSTRUCTION ENCODERS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "encode_lwz" that takes rt as Integer, d as Integer, ra as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: LWZ rt, d(ra): rt = MEM[ra + sign_extend(d)] (word, zero-extend)
    Return encode_d_form(PPC_OP_LWZ, rt, ra, d)
End Process

Process called "encode_lwzu" that takes rt as Integer, d as Integer, ra as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: LWZU rt, d(ra): rt = MEM[ra + d], ra = ra + d (load with update)
    Return encode_d_form(PPC_OP_LWZU, rt, ra, d)
End Process

Process called "encode_stw" that takes rs as Integer, d as Integer, ra as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: STW rs, d(ra): MEM[ra + sign_extend(d)] = rs
    Return encode_d_form(PPC_OP_STW, rs, ra, d)
End Process

Process called "encode_stwu" that takes rs as Integer, d as Integer, ra as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: STWU rs, d(ra): MEM[ra + d] = rs, ra = ra + d (store with update)
    Return encode_d_form(PPC_OP_STWU, rs, ra, d)
End Process

Process called "encode_lbz" that takes rt as Integer, d as Integer, ra as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: LBZ rt, d(ra): rt = zero_extend(byte at ra + d)
    Return encode_d_form(PPC_OP_LBZ, rt, ra, d)
End Process

Process called "encode_stb" that takes rs as Integer, d as Integer, ra as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: STB rs, d(ra): byte at MEM[ra + d] = low byte of rs
    Return encode_d_form(PPC_OP_STB, rs, ra, d)
End Process

Process called "encode_lhz" that takes rt as Integer, d as Integer, ra as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: LHZ rt, d(ra): rt = zero_extend(halfword at ra + d)
    Return encode_d_form(PPC_OP_LHZ, rt, ra, d)
End Process

Process called "encode_lha" that takes rt as Integer, d as Integer, ra as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: LHA rt, d(ra): rt = sign_extend(halfword at ra + d)
    Return encode_d_form(PPC_OP_LHA, rt, ra, d)
End Process

Process called "encode_sth" that takes rs as Integer, d as Integer, ra as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: STH rs, d(ra): halfword at MEM[ra + d] = low halfword of rs
    Return encode_d_form(PPC_OP_STH, rs, ra, d)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: COMPARE INSTRUCTION ENCODERS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "encode_cmpw" that takes bf as Integer, ra as Integer, rb as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    CMP (compare word, signed): compares ra and rb, sets CR field bf.
    X-form with opcode 31, XO 0. The L bit (bit 21) is 0 for 32-bit compare.
    bf is the CR field number (0-7), encoded in bits 25:23.
    @End Reasoning
    Let rt_field be shift_left(mask_bits(bf, 3), 2)
    Return encode_x_form(PPC_OP_ALU_EXT, rt_field, ra, rb, PPC_XO_CMP, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_cmplw" that takes bf as Integer, ra as Integer, rb as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: CMPL (compare logical word, unsigned): X-form, XO 32
    Let rt_field be shift_left(mask_bits(bf, 3), 2)
    Return encode_x_form(PPC_OP_ALU_EXT, rt_field, ra, rb, PPC_XO_CMPL, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_cmpwi" that takes bf as Integer, ra as Integer, si as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: CMPI (compare word immediate, signed): D-form, opcode 11
    Let rt_field be shift_left(mask_bits(bf, 3), 2)
    Return encode_d_form(PPC_OP_CMPI, rt_field, ra, si)
End Process

Process called "encode_cmplwi" that takes bf as Integer, ra as Integer, ui as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: CMPLI (compare logical word immediate, unsigned): D-form, opcode 10
    Let rt_field be shift_left(mask_bits(bf, 3), 2)
    Return encode_d_form(PPC_OP_CMPLI, rt_field, ra, ui)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: BRANCH INSTRUCTION ENCODERS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "encode_bc" that takes bo as Integer, bi as Integer, bd as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    BC (Branch Conditional): B-form. Branches if the condition specified by
    BO and BI is met. BD is a 14-bit signed word-aligned displacement.
    AA=0 (PC-relative), LK=0 (no link).
    @End Reasoning
    Return encode_b_form(PPC_OP_BC, bo, bi, bd, 0, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_bcl" that takes bo as Integer, bi as Integer, bd as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: BCL: Branch conditional and link. Same as BC but sets LK=1.
    Return encode_b_form(PPC_OP_BC, bo, bi, bd, 0, 1)
End Process

Process called "encode_b" that takes li as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: B (unconditional branch): I-form. LI is 24-bit signed word offset.
    Return encode_i_form(PPC_OP_B, li, 0, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_bl" that takes li as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: BL (branch and link): I-form with LK=1. Used for function calls.
    Return encode_i_form(PPC_OP_B, li, 0, 1)
End Process

Process called "encode_ba" that takes li as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: BA (branch absolute): I-form with AA=1.
    Return encode_i_form(PPC_OP_B, li, 1, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_bla" that takes li as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: BLA (branch and link absolute): I-form with AA=1, LK=1.
    Return encode_i_form(PPC_OP_B, li, 1, 1)
End Process

Process called "encode_blr" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    BLR (Branch to Link Register): returns from a function call.
    This is the XL-form BCLR with BO=20 (always), BI=0, LK=0.
    Encoding: opcode 19, BO=20, BI=0, BB=0, XO=16, LK=0
    @End Reasoning
    Return encode_xl_form(PPC_OP_BCLR, PPC_BO_ALWAYS, 0, 0, PPC_XO_BCLR, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_bctr" returns Integer:
    Note: BCTR (Branch to Count Register): XL-form BCCTR with BO=20, LK=0.
    Return encode_xl_form(PPC_OP_BCLR, PPC_BO_ALWAYS, 0, 0, PPC_XO_BCCTR, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_bctrl" returns Integer:
    Note: BCTRL (Branch to Count Register and Link): XL-form BCCTR with LK=1.
    Return encode_xl_form(PPC_OP_BCLR, PPC_BO_ALWAYS, 0, 0, PPC_XO_BCCTR, 1)
End Process

Process called "encode_beq" that takes bd as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: BEQ: branch if CR0[EQ] is set. BO=12 (true), BI=2 (EQ bit in CR0).
    Return encode_b_form(PPC_OP_BC, PPC_BO_TRUE, PPC_BI_EQ, bd, 0, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_bne" that takes bd as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: BNE: branch if CR0[EQ] is clear. BO=4 (false), BI=2 (EQ bit).
    Return encode_b_form(PPC_OP_BC, PPC_BO_FALSE, PPC_BI_EQ, bd, 0, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_blt" that takes bd as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: BLT: branch if CR0[LT] is set. BO=12, BI=0.
    Return encode_b_form(PPC_OP_BC, PPC_BO_TRUE, PPC_BI_LT, bd, 0, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_bgt" that takes bd as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: BGT: branch if CR0[GT] is set. BO=12, BI=1.
    Return encode_b_form(PPC_OP_BC, PPC_BO_TRUE, PPC_BI_GT, bd, 0, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_ble" that takes bd as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: BLE: branch if CR0[GT] is clear. BO=4, BI=1.
    Return encode_b_form(PPC_OP_BC, PPC_BO_FALSE, PPC_BI_GT, bd, 0, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_bge" that takes bd as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: BGE: branch if CR0[LT] is clear. BO=4, BI=0.
    Return encode_b_form(PPC_OP_BC, PPC_BO_FALSE, PPC_BI_LT, bd, 0, 0)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SPECIAL-PURPOSE REGISTER INSTRUCTIONS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "encode_mflr" that takes rt as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    MFLR rt: Move from Link Register. Copies LR into GPR rt.
    Encoded as MFSPR rt, 256 (SPR number for LR).
    MFSPR encoding uses split SPR number: bits 15:11 = SPR[4:0], bits 20:16 = SPR[9:5].
    For LR (SPR 256 = 0x100): SPR[4:0]=0, SPR[9:5]=8.
    So the encoding places 8 in the RA field and 0 in the RB field.
    @End Reasoning
    Return encode_x_form(PPC_OP_ALU_EXT, rt, 8, 0, PPC_XO_MFSPR, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_mtlr" that takes rs as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    MTLR rs: Move to Link Register. Copies GPR rs into LR.
    Encoded as MTSPR 256, rs. Same SPR split encoding as MFLR.
    @End Reasoning
    Return encode_x_form(PPC_OP_ALU_EXT, rs, 8, 0, PPC_XO_MTSPR, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_mfctr" that takes rt as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: MFCTR rt: Move from Count Register (SPR 288 = 9 shifted left by 5).
    Return encode_x_form(PPC_OP_ALU_EXT, rt, 9, 0, PPC_XO_MFSPR, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_mtctr" that takes rs as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: MTCTR rs: Move to Count Register.
    Return encode_x_form(PPC_OP_ALU_EXT, rs, 9, 0, PPC_XO_MTSPR, 0)
End Process

Process called "encode_sc" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    SC (System Call): invokes the operating system. The SC instruction has a
    fixed encoding with opcode 17 and specific bit patterns.
    Encoding: |17(6)|0(26-2)|0(1)|0(1)| with bit 1 set to 1.
    The actual encoding is 0x44000002.
    @End Reasoning
    Let encoded be shift_left(PPC_OP_SC, 26)
    Set encoded to encoded plus 2
    Return encoded
End Process

Process called "encode_nop" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    NOP on PowerPC is encoded as ORI 0,0,0 (ori r0, r0, 0).
    This is the canonical no-operation instruction.
    @End Reasoning
    Return encode_d_form(PPC_OP_ORI, 0, 0, 0)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: INSTRUCTION EMISSION TO OUTPUT BUFFER
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "emit_instruction" that takes output as Integer, instruction as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Writes a 32-bit PowerPC instruction to the output buffer in big-endian
    byte order (PowerPC is natively big-endian).
    @End Reasoning

    Let byte0 be instruction divided by 16777216
    Let byte1 be (instruction divided by 65536) minus (byte0 multiplied by 256)
    Let remainder be instruction minus (byte0 multiplied by 16777216) minus (byte1 multiplied by 65536)
    Let byte2 be remainder divided by 256
    Let byte3 be remainder minus (byte2 multiplied by 256)

    Set byte0 to mask_bits(byte0, 8)
    Set byte1 to mask_bits(byte1, 8)
    Set byte2 to mask_bits(byte2, 8)
    Set byte3 to mask_bits(byte3, 8)

    MachineCode.emit_byte(output, byte0)
    MachineCode.emit_byte(output, byte1)
    MachineCode.emit_byte(output, byte2)
    MachineCode.emit_byte(output, byte3)

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "emit_nop" that takes output as Integer returns Integer:
    Return emit_instruction(output, encode_nop())
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PSEUDO-INSTRUCTION ENCODERS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "encode_li" that takes output as Integer, rt as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    LI pseudo-instruction: loads a 32-bit immediate into a register.
    - If value fits in signed 16 bits: single ADDI rt, 0, value
    - Otherwise: LIS rt, upper16 followed by ORI rt, rt, lower16
    (LIS is ADDIS rt, 0, SI which loads SI shifted left by 16)
    @End Reasoning

    If value is greater than or equal to -32768:
        If value is less than or equal to 32767:
            Let instr be encode_addi(rt, 0, value)
            Return emit_instruction(output, instr)
        End If
    End If

    Let upper16 be value divided by 65536
    Let lower16 be value minus (upper16 multiplied by 65536)
    If value is less than 0:
        If lower16 is less than 0:
            Set lower16 to lower16 plus 65536
            Set upper16 to upper16 minus 1
        End If
    End If

    Set upper16 to mask_bits(upper16, 16)
    Set lower16 to mask_bits(lower16, 16)

    If lower16 is equal to 0:
        Set instr to encode_addis(rt, 0, upper16)
        Return emit_instruction(output, instr)
    End If

    Let lis_instr be encode_addis(rt, 0, upper16)
    emit_instruction(output, lis_instr)
    Let ori_instr be encode_ori(rt, rt, lower16)
    Return emit_instruction(output, ori_instr)
End Process

Process called "encode_mr" that takes ra as Integer, rs as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    MR (Move Register) pseudo-instruction: copies rs to ra.
    Implemented as OR ra, rs, rs.
    @End Reasoning
    Return encode_or(ra, rs, rs)
End Process
